- Save up enough to operate your household for at least 3 months

- If you are comfortable with more, then save up more

- When building your efund, treat it like a debt. Allocate as much money as you can to build it up each month

- List all debts smallest to largest
- Focus on paying the smallest first

- Use a budget to help visualize

20. Always keep the “why” in mind

Knowing WHY you are paying off your debt will help you push through when you feel like quitting 

Knowing WHY you are investing will help you get through those days of volatility

An unbeatable mindset

19. Kids are not the financial burden that you think they are

Are kids expensive? Absolutely

Did they keep us from paying off our debt and building wealth?

No.

You can view them as an excuse not to try or the motivation to push harder

Your choice

18. Utilize all tools at your disposal for building wealth.

- Get your 401k match
- Max out a Roth IRA
- Max out an HSA
- Auto contribute to a brokerage account

I didn’t start maxing out a Roth until nearly 7 years into my career

Cost me over $40,000 in growth

Start now!

17. A 9-5 is a tool, not your identity 

I used to view my job as a part of who I was as a person. 

Then I learned that I’m simply just a number on a spreadsheet

- Leverage your job to get income to buy more assets

Doing it any other way is going backwards

16. Not all advice is created equal

Many will offer advice along the way

While well intended, it might not be with your best interest in mind

Sometimes advice is given with the hopes that it steers you away from taking too much risk

This is often true with advice from family

15. Don’t forget to live life 

Whether you’re paying down debt or building assets remember that time is passing 

- Kids are growing up
- Parents are getting older

Its ok to grind to hit your goals but just look up every now and then and enjoy the season of life you are in.

14. An emergency fund is critical

Cash is always trash until you need it

That is exactly what an emergency fund is for

Life happens and having money set aside will keep you from tapping into your investments or going into credit card debt

Go for 3-6 months of expenses

13. Take advantage of your youth

If you are young, don’t pay down your mortgage.

Invest that money instead

You only get one life and these dollars during your younger years are the most valuable dollars you will ever earn

Your future self will thank you

12. A house is just a house

We have bought 3 houses and sold 2 over these 10 years.

Lived in old houses

Lived in new houses

In both cases memories were made that I will remember for the rest of my life

Just keep that in mind when making your house purchases.

11. Index funds are for 99% of people

I started off buying individual stocks and it was a disaster. 

It wasn’t until 2 years after paying off our debt that I discovered index funds

Simply buying and holding the whole market is a proven wealth building plan.

10. Simple investments are better

I invest in index funds because it’s something that I understand and it’s easily repeatable. 

Your idea of simple may be different and that’s ok

Complex doesn’t always mean it’s better 

Speaking of index funds 👇

9. You don’t have to spend more money to be happy

Some of the happiest moments of my life didn’t involve spending money

- Playing with my son in the yard
- Talking with my grandparents
- Enjoying being outdoors

Seeing money through this lens is the healthiest way to view it

8. The world is after your money

Companies spend millions of dollars to get you to separate yourself from your money through clever advertising

Simply keeping this in mind when seeing ads will help ensure that you keep more of your money and focus in on the goal

7. Technology is your friend

Today, there is no shortage of apps for making investing and budgeting easier

We used an app called Everydollar for our budget

Easy to use on the go

We used auto invest functions to ensure we kept investing.

Simple but important

6. Sacrifices are inevitable

You can only do so much with your income

Making the choice to cut back on spending and allocating funds to pay down debt or invest is not fun in the short term 

But once you see the debt shrink and the investments grow

You’ll be glad you did

5. Your spouse is your #1 asset

It’s cliche but it’s true: 

If you are married its imperative to be one the same page with your finances.

If you are not then you WILL struggle

My wife is hands down the reason why we are debt free and now building wealth

4. Budgets are essential

- (UTMA) Uniform Transfer to Minors Act

4. Investment accounts for kids (1/2)

Want to invest for your kids outside of a 529?

A custodial brokerage accounts may be the answer

An adult (custodian) is the owner of the account and makes contributions for the child

The money transfers to the child upon age of majority

Key points to remember:

- Anyone can contribute to these plans and anyone can be a beneficiary. 

- The money however can only be used for qualified education expenses. 

- Some states offer tax deductions on contributions

- Qualified distributions are tax free

3. Education accounts (2/2)

A second option is a Coverdell Education Savings Account.

This account must be set up before the beneficiary is 18 and can be used for an educational expenses.

3. Education accounts (1/2)

These accounts are great for investing in college or private school for kids. 

A 529 is the most popular option.

States offer their own type of 529 and each has their own investment options.

Key points to remember:

- Must have earned income to contribute to an IRA

2. Retirement accounts (2/2)

The company you work for may offer a 401(k)

If they do, make sure to contribute to it.

2. Retirement accounts (1/2)

The main difference between retirement accounts and a brokerage account is how they are taxed

Most common types are:
- Traditional IRA
- Roth IRA

For business owners:
- SEP IRAs
- SIMPLE IRAs
- Solo 401(k)s

Key points to remember:

- You must be a legal adult (18+) to contribute and have a SSN or tax ID number. 

- No limits to how much you can contribute

- Money can be withdrawn at any time

Get rid of those jokers and use the cash value to pay off debt

- Ignore interest rate

- Focus on the smallest debt first

- Once paid off use that former payment to pay off the second largest
